Conclusions:
Classical oncogene dependencies were strongly supported: BRAF dependency tracked braf_v600e, EGFR dependency tracked egfr_amplification, ERBB2 dependency tracked erbb2_amplification, and KRAS dependency tracked kras_mutation. The screen also contained broader lineage and molecular-context heterogeneity; pairwise subgroup screens frequently sharpened the effect beyond the single marker alone.
Noncanonical dependencies showed distinct feature contexts. KIF18A was enriched in high-aneuploidy contexts, TMED10 in high-WNT contexts, DHX9 in high-MYC-expression contexts, POLR2A in high-copy-number-8q24 contexts, and RPL11 in low-copy-number-9p21 contexts. RIT1 was weaker as a single-driver pattern but still had a statistically significant top subgroup from the systematic screen.
All dependency outcomes received at least one systematic heterogeneity screen; all final refined subgroup hypotheses state the complete pair of predicates selected by that screen.


